    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Skills for the Real World</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Florence Rosenthal letter on skills that are needed in real-life, in contrast to much of what is taught in colleges</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Colleges Post Average Rise in Tuition of 5 Percent'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Colleges Post Average Rise in Tuition of 5 Percent'' (news article, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>Let's not forget that what we need in the real world -- as opposed to the credentialed world -- are the basic skills, a k a speaking, listening, thinking, learning, reading, writing, calculating, button-pushing, working, cooperating, borrowing ideas and the asking of relevant questions so that we can learn the job on the job. That,  in addition to the home, is where  most of our integrated learning actually occurs.</p>
        <p>What we rarely use, on the other hand, are big bunches of disconnected subject matter that have been sort of memorized and then quickly forgotten as soon as the final examination is over.</p>
        <p>FLORENCE ROSENTHAL  Philadelphia, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a medical librarian.</p>
      </block>
